Question: How did you find participating in this experiment? Please tell us anything you'd like to share about your experience.
Response:
Got a diagnosis of ADHD intattentive / combined type later in life (age 30). 
- Reading comprehension passages felt a little bit exam-like, so felt nervous. What if I am stupid and get things wrong? Found myself overhearing the conversation in the next room and not reading the passages properly so opted to put on my noise cancelling headphones. 
- The made-up words exercise was more game-like and felt more fun. As I got used to it, I could tell when I didn't focus and there were ones I know I got wrong (i.e. didn't even read the word so just had to select left or right to move past it); and there were some where I know I accidentally pressed the wrong key. 
Really interesting considering I would class myself as "too literate / too verbose" at a young age and through school, but the variation in attention is definitely there. I don't know if I am also on the autism spectrum.
